    "Commentary Vol. 90": "And I say unto you (see on \"Matthew 5:18\"), repeating the solemn affirmation of the preceding sentence, because he was about to say what the Jews would be slow to believe, and what was of the greatest importance. From the east and west , (compare Isaiah `[char_Isaiah_Gen_26]` 45:6) from the farthest parts of the earth in every direction, from the remotest Gentile nations. Here is already an intimation that Christianity will spread to all nations. And shall sit down , literally recline (see margin Rev. Ver.), i. e. , at table. The custom of the Persians, which spread to the Greeks and Romans, had also been adopted by the Jews, viz., to lie on a couch while eating. This was placed beside the table, and on it the person reclined leaning on his left elbow, so as to take food from the table with his right hand, while the feet extended obliquely to the outside of the couch. Thus the feet could be washed while one was reclining (Luke 7:38, John `[char_John_Ref]` 13:4 f.); a man could lean his head back upon the breast, or lie \"in the bosom\" of one who reclined, behind him. (John `[char_John_Ref]` 13:23, John `[char_John_Ref]` 13:25, John `[char_John_Ref]` 1:18, Luke 16:23) This luxurious mode of eating had not been the usage of their ancestors; (see Genesis 27:19, Judges 19:6, 1 Samuel 20:24 f., where the Hebrew determines it to have been real y sitting) and the prophet Amos, (Amos 6:4, Amos 6:7) rebukes it as a part of the wicked luxury of the people, that they stretched themselves at their banquets. But in the time of our Lord it had become the universal custom, certainly at al formal meals, and to do otherwise would have seemed singular. Wherever in the N. T. 'sit,' 'sit down,' etc., are used with reference to eating, or where the phrase is 'sit at meat,' etc., the Greek always has some word denoting 'to recline'; and it is to be regretted that Rev. Ver. did not place this in the text rather than in the margin. Wyc., Tyn., and Great Bib. had 'rest,' Geneva and Rheims 'sit down.' With Abraham `[char_Abraham_Exo_17]`, Isaac, and Jacob `[char_Jacob_Ref]` . The Jews considered that their descent from these patriarchs made it certain that they would share with them the blessings of the Messianic reign; and the Rabbinical writings show that splendid entertainments, enjoyed with the patriarchs, belonged to their conception of the Messianic felicity, Here, as so often, our Saviour adapted himself to the common modes of expression. See the same image in Luke 14:15, Luke 16:28, the parables concerning feasts, and in Revelation 19:",
    "Commentary Vol. 91": "And I say unto you (see on \"Matthew 5:18\"), repeating the solemn affirmation of the preceding sentence, because he was about to say what the Jews would be slow to believe, and [v_Isa_45_6] what was of the greatest importance. From the east and west, (compare Isaiah `[char_Isaiah_Gen_26]` 45:6) from the farthest parts of the earth in every direction, from the remotest Gentile nations. Here is already an intimation that Christianity will spread to all nations. And shall sit down, literally recline (see margin Rev. Ver.), i. e., at table. The custom of the Persians `[nation_Persia_Ref]`, which spread to the Greeks and Romans, had also been adopted by the Jews, viz., to lie on a couch while eating. This was placed beside the table, and on it the person reclined leaning on his left elbow, so as to take food from the table with his right hand, while the feet extended obliquely to the outside of the couch. Thus the feet could be [v_Luk_7_38] washed while one was reclining (Luke 7:38, John `[char_John_Ref]` 13:4 f.); a man could lean his head back upon the [v_Jhn_13_23] breast, or lie \"in the bosom\" of one who reclined, behind him. (John `[char_John_Ref]` 13:23, John `[char_John_Ref]` 13:25, John `[char_John_Ref]` [v_Luk_16_23] 1:18, Luke 16:23) This luxurious mode of eating had not been the usage of their ancestors; [v_Gen_27_19] (see Genesis 27:19, Judges 19:6, 1 Samuel 20:24 f., where the Hebrew determines it to have been [v_Amo_6_4] really sitting) and the prophet Amos, (Amos 6:4, Amos 6:7) rebukes it as a part of the wicked luxury of the people, that they stretched themselves at their banquets. But in the time of our Lord it had become the universal custom, certainly at all formal meals, and to do otherwise would have seemed singular. Wherever in the N. T. 'sit,' 'sit down,' etc., are used with reference to eating, or where the phrase is 'sit at meat,' etc., the Greek always has some word denoting 'to recline'; and it is to be regretted that Rev. Ver. did not place this in the text rather than in the margin. Wyc., Tyn., and Great Bib. had 'rest,' Geneva and Rheims 'sit down.' With Abraham `[char_Abraham_Exo_17]`, Isaac, and Jacob `[char_Jacob_Ref]`. The Jews considered that their descent from these patriarchs made it certain that they would share with them the blessings of the Messianic reign; and the Rabbinical writings show that splendid entertainments, enjoyed with the patriarchs, belonged to their conception of the Messianic felicity, Here, as so often, our Saviour adapted himself to the common modes of expression. See the same image in Luke [v_Luk_16_28] 14:15, Luke 16:28, the parables concerning feasts, and in Revelation 19:"
