    "Dr. Peter S. Ruckman": "Pilate experienced the \u201cday of adversity\u201d and had within his hands the power to \u201cdeliver them that are drawn unto death, and those that are ready to be slain.\u201d The One who \u201cpondereth\u201d (not \u201cweighed,\u201d as in the faulty ASV, 1901) the hearts of men, weighed Cain (as He weighed Belshazzar) and found him wanting (Gen. 4:5\u201310). Cain became a fugitive and a vagabond, and Pilate had the dubious fame of having his name recorded in six books of the Holy Bible, where time and eternity can read of his infamous cowardice in \u201cthe day of adversity.\u201d A study of Cain and Pilate will throw such light on the \u201ccommentaries\u201d that one will be tempted to use them for children to sit on at the table. \u201cMy son, eat thou honey...which is sweet to thy taste: So shall the knowledge of wisdom be unto thy soul...and thy expectation shall not be cut off\u201d (vss. 13\u201314). The verses deal, obviously, with the believer\u2019s consumption of the word of God. Somehow, all of the scholars disconnect \u201cthe knowledge of wisdom\u201d as having any relation to the Bible! Exactly how this is done \u2014in view of 22:17\u201321 and 8:6\u201310\u2014is an amazing thing. Compare these three sets of passages and notice how the Holy Spirit (writing of His own words) clearly identifies them, interrelates them, ties the cross references together, and then puts the summary of the teachings in the first six verses in the Book!! One is tempted to believe that the commentators, as the Greek \u201clovers of wisdom\u201d (philosophers), have imagined that what they are writing\u2014ie., corrections of the Holy Bible\u2014are the fourteen words of wisdom\u201d and that knowledge of their writings is the \u201choney\u201d that makes the Bible palatable! [v_Psa_19_10] But the word of God is like honey (Psa. 19:10), it [v_1Sa_14_43] opens the eyes of those who taste it (1 Sam. 14:43), it is [v_Rev_10_9] sweet to the taste (Rev. 10:9), and the command to eat it [v_Pro_24_13] (Prov. 24:13) is an imperative. (Observe how neatly the Holy Spirit inserted 25:27 for men who \u201ceat the word\u201d of God and read, study, and learn it for the purpose of glorying in their ability to correct it! They puke!) Furthermore, observe the numerous parables which pop up in Proverbs 24 that can be applied to the Christian\u2019s walk, attitude, motives, witness, and work:\nverses 10\u201314, 16, 24, 26, 27, 30\u2013\n34. The \u201cson of God\u201d [v_Jhn_1_12] (John `[char_John_Ref]` 1:12\u201313) in the New Testament is commanded to [v_1Pe_2_1] feed on this word (1 Pet. 2:1\u20133); it will give him a knowledge of Wisdom (1 Cor. 1\u20132). When he attains this knowledge, he will walk \u201cwell pleasing\u201d unto his Lord and gain rewards at the Judgment Seat of Christ (24:14). He will not suffer the loss that the Christian of\nverse 12 suffers. (For \u201cexpectation,\u201d see notes under 23:17\u201318.) 15 Lay not wait, O wicked man, against the dwelling of the righteous; spoil not his resting place: 16 For a just man falleth seven times, and riseth up again: but the wicked shall fall into mischief. 17 Rejoice not when thine enemy falleth, and let not thine heart be glad when he stumbleth: 18 Lest the LORD see it, and it displease him, and he turn away his wrath from him. 19 Fret not thyself because of evil men, neither be thou envious at the wicked; 20 For there shall be no reward to the evil man; the candle of the wicked shall be put out. 21 My son, fear thou the LORD and the king: and meddle not with them that are given to change: 22 For their calamity shall rise suddenly; and who knoweth the ruin of them both? [v_Pro_24_15] Proverbs 24:15 is self explanatory and needs no comment. The Vulgate and the Septuagint\u2014both products of North Africa\u2014have invented several thoughts to replace the truth of the text, but none of them are worth repeating. \u201cFor a just man falleth seven times, and riseth up again: but the wicked shall fall into mischief\u2019 (vs. 16). The ASV (1901) mistakenly translates the second clause to mean that calamity will overthrow the wicked man. This is done by insisting on \u201caccuracy\u201d instead of \u201cclarity\u201d (see [v_Pro_16_27] old gimmick in Prov. 16:27) and then discovering that the Hebrew has the wrong preposition to match the corrupt reading. The \u201cBeth\u201d before the raah (Heb. text) cannot be translated \u201cBY\u201d here, for the verb preceding it is not in the Niphal, Hithpael, or any other partly \u201cpassive\u201d voice. The verb is a plain, out and out Qal, third person, plural, active. The Masoretic text reads \u201cstumble under adversity.\u201d The error of the ASV came, of course, from the RV of 1881, and Williams follows this corrupt thought in his comments on the verse. Again, the Septuagint reading is not worth reproducing. It is so far astray from any Hebrew manuscript extant that one would be foolish to suppose that the writer\u2014living after A.D. 150\u2014had a \u201cBible\u201d in mind when he invented the reading. The word \u201cmischief\u201d has already been commented on under 6:14,18 and 10:\n12. Williams: \u201cThe Hebrew of",
